This is a PhD thesis defense presentation in French. The presenter, Mathèse, is defending their dissertation on "Modeling the Invisible and Visible Impacts of Software Complexities on Commercial Services" (Modélisation des impacts invisibles et visibles de la complexité logicielle sur les services commerciaux).

The thesis aims to develop a model that can identify both visible and invisible impacts of software complexities on commercial services. The presenter explains that Frédéric, an employee, was tasked with purchasing new software for the company's commercial service. Although he thought he made a good deal by choosing the cheaper option, the software's complexity ended up causing problems for the sales team.

Mathèse argues that this experience highlights the importance of considering the hidden impacts of software complexities on commercial services. The presenter claims that most existing models do not account for these invisible effects and therefore fail to accurately predict the outcomes of software purchases.

To address this gap, Mathèse proposes a new model that combines qualitative and quantitative data from interviews with buyers, managers, and users. This model aims to identify both visible (e.g., increased costs) and invisible (e.g., reduced employee motivation) impacts of software complexities on commercial services.

The presenter argues that this research will have significant implications for companies and policymakers seeking to optimize their software purchasing decisions. By developing a simple, socio-economic model that can predict the hidden effects of software complexities, Mathèse hopes to improve working conditions and organizational performance in various industries.

Overall, the presentation aims to demonstrate the importance of considering the invisible impacts of software complexities on commercial services and to propose a novel approach for addressing these issues through modeling.

This is a French speech about the concept of zero-shot learning in artificial intelligence. The speaker describes how traditional machine learning approaches require large amounts of labeled data to learn from examples, but in real-world applications, it's often difficult or impossible to collect such data.

The speaker then explains that their research focuses on developing an AI system that can recognize objects and species without needing any training data at all - just by looking at a single image. This is achieved by learning the relationships between images and text descriptions, allowing the AI to make predictions about new, unseen data.

To demonstrate this concept, the speaker shows examples of identifying different animal species (tiger, bear, etc.) from just one image per category. They then describe how their system uses a binary compatibility function to match the output of an AI model with the correct label.

The speaker also mentions that they have trained their model using only text descriptions and images of birds, and tested its ability to identify new bird species without any additional training data. The results show that the AI model was able to correctly identify most of the species, even though it had never seen a single specimen before.

Overall, the speech highlights the potential applications of zero-shot learning in various fields, such as medical diagnosis, protein identification, or object recognition.

**Title:** "Big Data in Healthcare: Unlocking the Secrets of Infertility"

**Summary:**

The speaker discusses the importance of big data in healthcare, specifically in the context of infertility. They highlight that one out of four couples struggle with infertility, and that there is a lack of research on this topic. The goal of their thesis is to analyze and understand these big data to improve the treatment of infertile women.

The speaker shares their findings, which include:

1. The creation of a "family" dataset containing information about women's health, including their medical history, treatments, and outcomes.
2. The development of an algorithm that can identify patterns and correlations within this dataset.
3. The discovery that there are 150,000 women treated for infertility in France every year, with the average age increasing annually.

**Translation:**

"Ah, la mort. It's a life-changer. Boulouverre is when we flip everything at once. It's so powerful that we want to merge forever with our well-being. Create a solid bond, build a family, have a child. But having a baby can sometimes be more difficult than expected. Did you know that one out of four couples don't get pregnant after trying for a year? Statistically, in this room, there are infertile couples. And yet, I won't talk about your infertility, personally no. You might wonder if I'll explore the question of infertility; I won't do door-to-door. Knock-knock, madame and monsieur, are you infertile? Clack-clack, opening doors one by one. That's where we got a superbidée.

Use the vital statistics card. During their lifetime, on average, people forget. What about when we open a door with this vital statistics card at the doctor's office? At least once. Thanks to this vital statistics card, medical surveillance is possible. Storing these details on secure servers, every person's data, in all of France. The overflow, where votes are counted, and this has been going on for two years. This enormous amount of information is what we call big data in healthcare. Mega-net health in French. It's a true treasure trove. My thesis goal is to tame these big data using algorithms to extract the necessary information to explore the question of fertility. But above all, translate them into medical language. It's like having millions of pearls, big data that have passed through different news networks, algorithm formed necklaces. Each necklace represents a woman's infertility treatment journey. We could learn which zones are most effective and what medications work best. Or even if poor women have a higher risk of infertility than others. But since no one was interested in this question before my thesis, I had to start by creating an inventory of existing infertility treatments: consultations, medications, care, ultrasound tests, a sort of health catalog, based on their colors, size, shape... And I could show that there are at least 150,000 women treated every year in France. That's roughly 75 times the Olympia. And these women get older and older each year, so their chances of treatment success decrease annually."

Please let me know if you'd like me to clarify or expand on any points!

That's why I will test whether sea salt water reduces pain during blood sampling and if placing a compress near an umbilical catheter allows for even greater pain reduction during blood sampling. When designing materials that come into contact with biological systems, it's crucial to ensure biocompatibility. This means avoiding toxic substances and creating materials that are gentle on living tissues.

Polydopamine, or PDA, is a remarkable molecule that exhibits several unique properties. It can form tiny particles called nanoparticles, expand into thin films, or adopt the shape of a sheet. This versatility makes it an attractive material for various applications.

Here's my attempt:

"I'm reminded of a TV show called 'Rendez-vous in Unknown Territory,' where celebrities immerse themselves in the life of a distant population. That's similar to what I do, but without the media hype, that's anthropology! Anthropology is interested in different ways and customs, inviting us to put our own way of life into perspective. And me, I'm at the material unknown, imagine great mountains, a village at 3,500 meters altitude, a population of around 300 people. The population has had nothing easy, from which they have become ingrown, we are in a village in the Himalayas. This is where I spent several months living in immersion with an indigenous Tititee population. I laughed with these people, drank tea with them, spoke their language, why? Because it's the research method of my field of study, participant observation. You talk to people, you build trust, and they give you honest words.

I don't hide from you that the first contact was a bit difficult. I remember, I knocked on the door of a village, and there was no response. Another village, I didn't see anything, it's just the usual, nothing special. In fact, it's not like our cities; we need to adjust ourselves. I didn't knock again. I sat in the family kitchen, four pairs of eyes looked at me with questioning gazes. They finally accepted me, they served me more jambois, and when I left, I don't know how to get back. But eventually, I settled into living with this family where there are two medical doctors from our village.

So what do I observe? I observe a significant intergenerational gap. There's the father, who still practices traditional medicine with his father. Meanwhile, his son has become well-educated and has access to more knowledge. He can travel to the West and practice modern medicine. And today, he travels and faces new visions of the world that bring him back to his village. This makes him question tradition, for example, making more use of these medicines, the entire medical system that goes with tourists on passage. Something that are perceived as not appreciated at first, but which might be accepted later.

Finally, there's something in the father's words: 'Yes, sure, life in the village today is easier, but I don't see men like before, walking across the mountain, I wonder what will happen next to ensure our traditional healing methods if my son leaves this way.' So that's anthropology. It's observing how a society evolves, submerging ourselves in unknown territory to understand what makes us human beings."

And tonight, without having found the perpetrator, we've revealed the fingerprints that will lead us to his identity - a child's game in complete darkness.

**TRANSCRIPT:** (Translated from French)

"I have very bad news. Your house is infested with mice. They're everywhere. So what do you do? Do you, like the enemies of Medjugorie, clean out your entire house? But remember, the end of the episode, the mouse is always there. Where are you going to trap each of the mice and eliminate them one by one? Some mice will always be left over. Then, surely, you'll think about buying a mousetrap. But can we apply this simple reasoning to the fight against cancer? When chemotherapy, which casts its shadow everywhere and targeted therapy doesn't work, couldn't we use a mousetrap? The goal of my thesis is to turn this idea into reality. My mouse is glioblastoma, a particularly aggressive brain cancer that neither surgery, nor radiation therapy, nor chemotherapy can completely eliminate. The first step has been developed the structure of this trap. We want it to be camouflaged, it must therefore resemble the brain as much as possible. I used its main component, hyaluronic acid, which you find everywhere in the body. The problem is that it degrades quickly. It needs to stay long enough in the brain for the glioblastoma cells to migrate into the trap. I mixed it with silk fibers from silkworms and created a micro-foam sponge material, allowing for the migration of penetrated cells. The second step is identifying a target. Studies have shown that Glioblastoma cells responsible for the recurrence of cancer after treatment are attracted by the SDF1 protein. So I loaded my sponge with this little cheese for Glioblastoma. The idea is to set up a trap, and then leave it in place for the surgeon to remove as much of the tumor as possible. Our trap has caught on time, the infiltrated cell that the surgeon can't remove. There's still a lot to do before this trap becomes functional, and we don't know yet what will be most effective at eliminating the captured cells. But maybe one day, thanks to it, you'll be able to say: I have very good news. You no longer have mice in your house."
